          div.back.back__bigdata
            p.text.text__bigdata
              | Big Data is an oft-touted term that has no commonly agreed-upon 
              | definition despite its prevalent use.
              | The overall purpose of this group is to look at how Big Data, defined
              | as "uncomfortable data", can inform,
              | empower, and/or disrupt R&amp;D organizations based on how they 
              | manage their R&amp;D processes with or without its use
      div.flip-container(ontouchstart='this.classList.toggle("hover");')
        div.flipper
          div.front
            p.img-thumbnail: img(src='assets/images/collaboration.jpg' alt='Collaboration Icon')
            p: strong Collaboration
          div.back.back__collab
            p.text.text__collab
              | Considering the ubiquitousness of internet connectivity and smart 
              | devices, instantaneous communication and collaboration has become 
              | commonplace. The pace of development of tools that enable 
              | real-time collaboration from anywhere has also witnessed 
              | an explosion recently. How can R&amp;D organizations 
              | navigate the landscape of these tools to the best effect?
      div.flip-container(ontouchstart='this.classList.toggle("hover");')
        div.flipper
          div.front
            p.img-thumbnail: img(src='assets/images/ves.jpg' alt='Virtual Experimentation and Simulation Icon')
            p: strong Virtual Experimentation &amp; Simulation
          div.back.back__ves
            p.text.text__ves
              | Any physical experiment necessarily 
              | includes a set of data that is not quantifiable; results from each iteration carry 
              | intuition that researchers develop throughout their careers based
              | on the expectations of how real world conditions affect their experiments. However, 
              | twenty-first century research requires much more use of virtual 
              | laboratories and simulation software 
              | that mimic real world conditions. How do we gain trust in such 
              | simulations knowing that they may not capture conditions perfectly?
  
